@end menu

@node Overview
@chapter Overview

The daemon uses configuration-directory mode.  One daemon process owns one BlueZ
system-bus connection, one ALSA Sequencer client, and one runtime session per
configured BLE-MIDI device.  Each configured device gets a stable ALSA port
inside the daemon's ALSA client.  BLE link drops and reconnect cycles change the
session state, but they do not recreate the local ALSA port.

The project treats BLE-MIDI devices generically.  A specific instrument such as
Roland GO:KEYS is a profile or quirk case, not the conceptual model of the
runtime.

@node Daemon
@chapter Daemon

Run the daemon with a configuration directory:

@example
midi-ble-rtd --config ~/.config/midi-ble-rt
@end example

The alias @option{--config-dir} is also accepted.  Version commands are:

@example
midi-ble-rtd -v
midi-ble-rtd -vv
@end example

The verbose form prints the daemon role, runtime mode, compiled feature summary,
and realtime defaults.

@node Control CLI
@chapter Control CLI

@command{midi-ble-rtctl} provides BlueZ preparation commands, daemon control
commands, and diagnostics commands.

Common BlueZ/device commands:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl list
midi-ble-rtctl scan
midi-ble-rtctl info DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl probe DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl pair DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl trust DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl untrust DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl connect DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl configure DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl disconnect DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl forget DEVICE
@end example

Daemon control commands require a running @command{midi-ble-rtd} instance:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-ping
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-status
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-list
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-connect DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-disconnect DEVICE
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-recheck DEVICE
@end example

@command{daemon-status} prints one @samp{OK STATUS} line.  Fields include:

@table @code
@item devices
Number of configured device sessions known to the daemon.
@item streaming
Number of configured device sessions currently in STREAMING state.
@item alsa_tx_thread
Shared ALSA Sequencer TX thread state: @samp{running} or @samp{stopped}.
@item rx_workers, tx_workers
Number of per-device runtime worker threads currently allocated.
@item rtkit
Whether RTKit scheduling was requested by daemon configuration.
@item rtkit_priority
Configured RTKit realtime priority after daemon-side clamping.
@item rtkit_rx, rtkit_tx
Whether RTKit is enabled for RX and TX runtime worker classes.
@item lifecycle_busy
Whether the lifecycle/control-plane queue is currently executing a command.
@item lifecycle_queue
Number of pending lifecycle/control-plane commands.
@end table

Example:

@example
OK STATUS devices=1 streaming=1 alsa_tx_thread=running rx_workers=1 tx_workers=1 rtkit=on rtkit_priority=1 rtkit_rx=on rtkit_tx=off lifecycle_busy=no lifecycle_queue=0
@end example

@node Configuration
@chapter Configuration

A typical configuration directory has this layout:

@example
~/.config/midi-ble-rt/
  daemon.ini
  devices.d/
    controller.ini
@end example

Common @file{daemon.ini} keys:

@table @code
@item [defaults].pair
Pair configured devices by default.
@item [defaults].trust
Set BlueZ @samp{Trusted=true} by default.
@item [defaults].reconnect_on_link_loss
Reconnect sessions after BLE link loss.
@item [defaults].enable_tx
Enable ALSA-to-BLE MIDI transmit path by default.
@item [gatt].service_uuid
BLE-MIDI service UUID.
@item [gatt].io_uuid
BLE-MIDI I/O characteristic UUID.
@item [gatt].io_uuid_alias
Optional alternate characteristic UUID for device-specific aliases.
@item [gatt].require_notify
Require notification support on the selected BLE-MIDI characteristic.
@item [gatt].require_write_without_response
Require Write Without Response support for TX.
@item [daemon].client_name
ALSA Sequencer client name.  Default: @samp{midi-ble-rt}.
@item [alsa].port_name
Default ALSA port name for configured devices.
@item [stats].enabled
Enable runtime @file{stats.tsv} export.
@item [stats].interval_ms
Stats export interval in milliseconds.
@item [stats].latency_diagnostics
Enable runtime @file{latency.tsv} diagnostics export.
@end table

Common @file{devices.d/*.ini} keys:

@table @code
@item [device].id
Stable local device identifier.
@item [device].address
Bluetooth device address.
@item [device].name
Human-readable device name.
@item [device].profile
Device profile name.  Use @samp{standard_ble_midi} for generic BLE-MIDI devices
or a specific profile such as @samp{roland_gokeys} when a quirk is required.
@item [device].alsa_port_name
ALSA port name for this configured device.
@item [device].enabled
Whether this device config is active.
@item [device].connect_on_start
Connect this configured device during daemon startup.
@item [policy].pair
Override default pairing policy for this device.
@item [policy].trust
Override default BlueZ trust policy for this device.
@item [policy].reconnect_on_link_loss
Override default reconnect policy for this device.
@item [midi].enable_tx
Override default ALSA-to-BLE transmit policy for this device.
@end table

@node Realtime
@chapter Realtime

RTKit support is configured in @file{daemon.ini}:

@table @code
@item [realtime].rtkit
Request RTKit realtime scheduling.
@item [realtime].realtime_rx
Apply RTKit to RX worker threads when RTKit is enabled.  Default: yes.
@item [realtime].realtime_tx
Apply RTKit to TX worker threads when RTKit is enabled.  Default: no.
@item [realtime].rt_priority
RTKit realtime priority.  The daemon clamps the value to its supported range.
@end table

RTKit status is visible through:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-status
@end example

The status output reports @code{rtkit}, @code{rtkit_priority}, @code{rtkit_rx},
and @code{rtkit_tx}.

@node Diagnostics
@chapter Diagnostics

The diagnostics commands are:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl stats [--path PATH]
midi-ble-rtctl top [--path PATH] [--interval MS]
midi-ble-rtctl latency [--path PATH]
midi-ble-rtctl latency-top [--path PATH] [--interval MS]
@end example

@command{stats} and @command{top} read @file{stats.tsv}.  @command{latency} and
@command{latency-top} read @file{latency.tsv}, which is exported only when
latency diagnostics are enabled in configuration.

@node Files
@chapter Files

Runtime files are written below @file{$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/midi-ble-rt}, or below the
system temporary directory if @env{XDG_RUNTIME_DIR} is not set.

@table @file
@item control.sock
Local daemon control socket used by @command{midi-ble-rtctl}.
@item stats.tsv
Runtime packet, byte, drop, queue, and session statistics.
@item latency.tsv
Optional latency diagnostics file.
@end table

Installed documentation normally includes:

@table @file
@item midi-ble-rtd(1)
Daemon manual page.
@item midi-ble-rtctl(1)
Control CLI manual page.
@item midi-ble-rt.info
GNU Info manual, when built with @command{makeinfo}.
@end table

@node Examples
@chapter Examples

Scan for BLE-MIDI devices:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl scan --timeout 10 --midi-only
@end example

Prepare a Roland GO:KEYS profile and write configuration:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl connect CB:81:F4:62:FF:07 --profile roland_gokeys --write-config
@end example

Start the daemon:

@example
midi-ble-rtd --config ~/.config/midi-ble-rt
@end example

Check daemon state:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-status
@end example

View detailed help for daemon status fields:

@example
midi-ble-rtctl help daemon-status
midi-ble-rtctl daemon-status --help
@end example

@bye
